commit_message:
Create member role while running validate-tempest role

https://review.opendev.org/#/c/638617/ patch comes in tempestconf
-2.2.0 which looks for member role not Member role and then
sets auth.tempest_roles otherwise it removes the section which
leads to tempestconf generation failure

Creating member role fixes the issue.

Closes-Bug: #1828859

Change-Id: I77863fdb8153a6ea2d2b148a90af38899e1b304e
Signed-off-by: Chandan Kumar (raukadah) <chkumar@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add a UUID to the extra-hardware data on ppc64le

The extra-hardware collector uses dmidecode[1] to extract a UUID.  As
ppc64le doesn't support DMI it doesn't get one.  It turns out the
ppc64le platforms don't actually have a UUID (yet[2]).

This change looks for a UUID in the extra data and if one isn't found
generates one from the vendor and serial data if found.

I also have [3] to just put all this logic in python-hardware.

[1] https://github.com/redhat-cip/hardware/blob/master/hardware/detect.py#L419-L427
[2] https://github.com/open-power/skiboot/issues/193
[3] https://github.com/redhat-cip/hardware/pull/46
Story: 2003520

Change-Id: Iea5328ce3cc9c66c164277b0b929c52d444ad651

commit_message:
[DHCP] Don't resync network if same port is alredy in cache

Sometimes when port is created on dhcp agent's side, it may happend
that same port is already in network cache.
Before this patch if port with same IP address was already in cache,
resync was rescheduled because of duplicate IPs found in cache.

Now resync will be scheduled only if duplicate IP address belongs to
port with different MAC address or different id.

Change-Id: I23afbc10725f5dc78e3c63e6e505ef89ba8dc4a5
Closes-Bug: #1824802
(cherry picked from commit 5c433a027daab2419d974820589205253871885e)

commit_message:
Cap keyring and scikit-learn on python2

keyring drops py2 support so lets ensure our requirements wont allow us
to install 19.X releases on py2.

scikit-learn drops support for 3.4 or lower with release 0.21.0.

Setting the minimum supported python for both to 3.4 to be consistent
with u-c. When we remove the 3.4 constraints we'll also need to fix g-r

NOTE(dmllr) Sphinx cap is not needed on ocata as it already had
a much more restrictive cap.

NOTE(tonyb): The more modern branches allow networkx >= 2.0.  These
version are explictly blocked on ocata so we no longer squash
I0a9700926c9a0db93e782c853c33f1aaee3d4876

NOTE(dmllr): Fix typo.

Change-Id: If558f184c959e4b63b56dec3ca1571d1034cfe5c
Signed-off-by: Matthew Thode <mthode@mthode.org>

commit_message:
Add manifest list image support to the kolla builder

Working towards manifest list image support for the undercloud images using the
kolla builder.  Working on functionality to "just work" gathering the
individual image tags in the manifest list image, and maintaining previous
functionality for each image in the manifest list.

Change-Id: Ib2b67ba47b35f296162dd255043bbe33fdfbd8f1

isn't available.  Recently ceph-ansible added support to only run the
'dummy' container on x86_64 hosts, this measn that all other hosts will
need the ceph tool to complete the install.

Related-Bug: 1790043
Change-Id: Ia35466780e2b29da5c5661f586221e4fdb68a54c
"}]
commit_message:
Add ceph-common into the overcloud images

Currently we're using the ceph container to generate keys for client
only nodes.  This fails on architectures (ppc64ke) where that container
isn't available.  Recently ceph-ansible added support to only run the
'dummy' container on x86_64 hosts, this measn that all other hosts will
need the ceph tool to complete the install.

This change adds the ceph-common package into the overcloud images.

Related-Bug: 1790043
Change-Id: Ia35466780e2b29da5c5661f586221e4fdb68a54c

Handle all exceptions loading pickled data

The pickle file is just a local cache of Gerrit data. If we fail to
load it, it will just be regenerated from Gerrit. We should never
allow a failure in pickle.load to be fatal.

Change-Id: If433fa5f335db8db63cdd264919c0dbeb3a7a32e

commit_message:
[DHCP] Don't resync network if same port is alredy in cache

Sometimes when port is created on dhcp agent's side, it may happend
that same port is already in network cache.
Before this patch if port with same IP address was already in cache,
resync was rescheduled because of duplicate IPs found in cache.

Now resync will be scheduled only if duplicate IP address belongs to
port with different MAC address or different id.

Change-Id: I23afbc10725f5dc78e3c63e6e505ef89ba8dc4a5
Closes-Bug: #1824802
(cherry picked from commit 5c433a027daab2419d974820589205253871885e)

commit_message:
Performance improvement for non-udp health checks

When no UDP listeners are present, skip the UDP health-check code
branch, which prevents expensive and unnecessary DB calls.
Also optimise the UDP health-check code so it only fetches information
for relevant listeners.

Co-Authored-By: Adam Harwell <flux.adam@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I7fde54084b39c1d0529cfb0bcfb79697d63ea6ae
(cherry picked from commit 24e77d606dce174acf16fadcf32ba4b5182aa49a)

commit_message:
Fluent-logging: Remove utils for generating configuration files

This removes the utilities for generating the fluentd, fluentbit,
and parser configuration files from yaml and moves to instead
consume the configuration files as strings from the values.yaml.

This allows for easier creation and maintenance of configuration
files for fluentd and fluentbit, as the utilities became unwieldy
with complex configuration files.

This necessitated the removal of the core test executed by the
charts helm tests, but this would be required as we move to split
the charts regardless

Change-Id: Ied4a76bbdf58b54a6d702db04a7120b64f54dcac
Signed-off-by: Steve Wilkerson <sw5822@att.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2019-05-23 22:48:09.000000000', 'message': 'Fix NFS/CIFS share creation failure issue

When the image count is over 25, there might not get
manila-service-image, because current manila shares
creation is using novaclient to get image info, but
novaclient can only get 25 images due to pagination
of glance server, So this change is to switch to use
glanceclient instead of novaclient to get image info,
because glanceclient can iter all image info, while
novaclient is rarely maintained with stuff of image

commit_message:
Fix NFS/CIFS share creation failure issue

When the image count is over 25, there might not get
manila-service-image, because current manila shares
creation is using novaclient to get image info, but
novaclient can only get 25 images due to pagination
of glance server, So this change is to switch to use
glanceclient instead of novaclient to get image info,
because glanceclient can iter all image info, while
novaclient is rarely maintained with stuff of image
API.

Change-Id: Id905d47600bda9923cebae617749c8286552ec94
Closes-Bug: #1741425
(cherry picked from commit 51dd510636c817d2f7b5cb0b3c967fb604de87bb)

commit_message:
undercloud-setup: Introduce tripleo_set_unique_hostname variable

In hostname playbook, add a task to modify /etc/hosts.
tripleo_set_unique_hostname is a new boolean which if set to true,
will add a line to /etc/hosts with an unique hostname
( {{ ansible_hostname }}-unique ) which will resolve the first IPv4
address found in the inventory.

It is useful to reproduce a deployment where the operator is using
hostnames to create SSL certificates and deploy the undecloud with the
public host being an hostname/fqdn and not an IP address.

Related-Bug: #1763776
Change-Id: I6425499e5d248e6cb2285f14dd9c6e716122b90b

commit_message:
[DHCP] Don't resync network if same port is alredy in cache

Sometimes when port is created on dhcp agent's side, it may happend
that same port is already in network cache.
Before this patch if port with same IP address was already in cache,
resync was rescheduled because of duplicate IPs found in cache.

Now resync will be scheduled only if duplicate IP address belongs to
port with different MAC address or different id.

Change-Id: I23afbc10725f5dc78e3c63e6e505ef89ba8dc4a5
Closes-Bug: #1824802
(cherry picked from commit 5c433a027daab2419d974820589205253871885e)

commit_message:
Disable limit if affinity(anti)/same(different)host is requested

When max_placement_results is less than the total number of nodes in
a deployment it may not be possible to use the affinity, anti-affinity,
same host or different host filters as there is no guarantee
for placement to return the expected hosts under such situations. This
patch disables the max_placement_results parameter when nova queries
placement for ``GET /allocation_candidates`` if the
request_spec.scheduler_hints containts any of group, same_host or
different_host keys.

Note that due to change If7ea02df42d220c5042947efdef4777509492a0b only
being in Train the test in the backport calls resources_from_request_spec
without the context or fake HostManager parameters.

Change-Id: Ia2d5f80b6db59a8f6da03344aeaa6aa599407672
Closes-Bug: #1827628
(cherry picked from commit 2f9e972ba3358fc5bc9bdc06faf47b21d509e20f)

commit_message:
Log when the placement service plugin is used wrongly

Log explicitly when an invalid plugin combination is requested in the
config.

The placement service plugin cannot be used with non-ML2 core
plugins. neutron-server already exits when misconfigured like that
(when a plugin raises an uncaught exception in its __init__())
so I didn't change anything about that. This change only adds a more
explicit log message for this misconfiguration.

Change-Id: Ida1a3188f8b3145cf270d280bf942b3950c0779c
Related-Bug: #1578989
Related-Bug: #1818479

commit_message:
Allow first address in an IPv6 subnet as valid unicast

When looking at the RFC [1], there's no mention that this can't be the
gateway address.  Permit it.

[1] https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc4291#section-2.6.1

Change-Id: I3f2905c2c4fca02406dfa3c801c166c14389ba41
Fixes-Bug: #1682094
(cherry picked from commit 1916bc5c0627ca24e312ca55ea62c8df7eb8f158)

In buster, using this to install a keyring package doesn't work anymore:

commit_message:
Fix setting-up Buster's backport repository

In buster, using this to install a keyring package doesn't work anymore:
apt-get -y --allow-unauthenticated install keyring-package

Therefore, we must fallback to installing the key manually with apt-key
instead, which is what this patch does.

Change-Id: Ie46cb489f84a1390b87e0d9299406f944dca1c49

commit_message:
Revert directory structure

Directory structure which generated by tempest-plugin-cookiecutter has been
changed, and generated new directory named <repo_name>_tempest_tests has been
moved under <repo_name> to <repo_name>/<repo_name>

e.g. )
project: Ironic
repo_name: ironic
testclass: IronicTempestPlugin

system@takada-dev:/opt/stack/ironic$ cookiecutter https://git.openstack.org/openstack/tempest-plugin-cookiecutter

[before]
/opt/stack/ironic
  ironic_tempest_plugin
    config.py
    plugin.py
    tests/
      api/
      scenario/
    services/
      client.py

[after]
/opt/stack/ironic
  ironic
    ironic_tempest_plugin
      config.py
      plugin.py
      tests/
        api/
        scenario/
      services/
        client.py

This patch set fixes this bug.

Change-Id: Ib4f33a9f816b59b7d5eb0ac8c3f966bba4c71908
Closes-Bug: #1517310

subject: Fix where we use constraints
messages:
[{'account_id': 12898, 'date': '2019-05-16 08:33:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2019-05-16 13:20:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Wouldn't it be better to update the generate target to override its install_command?

I see a wide mix of this in other projects with the constraints being in either install_command or deps. I suppose it is only an issue for us though since we are probably the only ones that need certain jobs to run unconstrained."}, {'account_id': 14288, 'date': '2019-05-16 14:13:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 12898, 'date': '2019-05-24 00:26:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> Wouldn't it be better to update the generate target to override its
 > install_command?
 > 
 > I see a wide mix of this in other projects with the constraints
 > being in either install_command or deps. I suppose it is only an
 > issue for us though since we are probably the only ones that need
 > certain jobs to run unconstrained.

Using constraints in install_command is wrong and will break any project that is also listed in constraints.

For our use case adding it into install_command for the generate testenv will work but IMO introduces a small amount of cognitive dissidence so I prefer to keep all projects following the same "template".

Hopefully once the constraints-update topic is empty on master we wont see that anymore.  (If we do we should fix it)'}, {'account_id': 12898, 'date': '2019-05-24 00:26:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Cherry Picked

This patchset was cherry picked to branch stable/stein as commit 73f491ffb50fc29db552c1655639fac45b9056e1'}]

as it means the generate env will be run in a constrained environment.

We don't use UPPER_CONSTRAINT_FILE as *right now* it's the same thing

Change-Id: Ia61d944dbfdf494598e41e5fbefd0e32a91814ed

commit_message:
Fix where we use constraints

in I2598503c2d4397d7efbb03a76df9a4e91dd0c1cf we mistakenly added
constraints to install_command in out based testenv.  This is incorrect
as it means the generate env will be run in a constrained environment.

We don't use UPPER_CONSTRAINT_FILE as *right now* it's the same thing
and this leaves us internally consistent (even if technically incorrect)

Change-Id: Ia61d944dbfdf494598e41e5fbefd0e32a91814ed

commit_message:
Set the lower limit of api_version for volume_type

In boot server API, the volume_type is supported by microversion 2.67.
Therefore, the lower limit of the volume_type should be added to the CLI
command, otherwise an exception will occur.

Co-Authored-By: Eric Xie <eric_xiett@163.com>

Closes-Bug: #1829854
Change-Id: Ie909c16568b017ca0acc802194140da7bece76c5
(cherry picked from commit 7b9d3000893aefa9c5efc77b50dc0fec5cab29be)

commit_message:
Raise os-traits os-resource-classes constraints

Because os-traits and os-resource-classes are libraries that
provide enumerations, we usually want whatever the latest
version is, even in lower-constraints.txt. We haven't, however,
been good about keeping those up to date.

This updates both requriements.txt and lower-constraints.txt to
the latest versions of both os-traits and os-resource-clases.

No change is required is global upper-constraints. That already
has the latest.

Change-Id: I0bd0e8e071d6275c3e21556018d476c97e8533ae
Story: 2005651
Task: 30939

commit_message:
Set force_config_drive only when OVNMetadata is disabled

There are usecases when operator wants to talk to metadata API from
config-drive script (e.g. using curl to get data from metadata). That
means it makes sense to have OVN Metadata Agent deployed while forcing
config-drive to be used.

This patch sets force_config_drive to true only when OVNMetadataEnable
is set to false. If it's set to true then it doesn't touch
force_config_drive option, leaving it up to environment to define it.
(The default for force_config_drive is false.)

Conflicts:
    deployment/ovn/ovn-controller-container-puppet.yaml

Closes-Bug: #1830179
Change-Id: Ib956ff2f521b9853c58eaa5500836c692dd9321d
(cherry picked from commit 7ac8e67d82e688382c3ea13c48b0cb55f759117b)

commit_message:
Fix NFS/CIFS share creation failure issue

When the image count is over 25, there might not get
manila-service-image, because current manila shares
creation is using novaclient to get image info, but
novaclient can only get 25 images due to pagination
of glance server, So this change is to switch to use
glanceclient instead of novaclient to get image info,
because glanceclient can iter all image info, while
novaclient is rarely maintained with stuff of image
API.

Change-Id: Id905d47600bda9923cebae617749c8286552ec94
Closes-Bug: #1741425

commit_message:
standalone/undercloud - post: use EndpointMap to fetch Keystone URL

Using EndpointMap to ensure we get the hostname/fqdn if possible
otherwise it fallbacks to the IP for Keystone public endpoint.

This is useful when the operator uses a certificate based on
hostname/fqdn and not an IP address.

Closes-Bug #1763776
Change-Id: Ifa9d55cca90caf5be0c83507cb47447e25311fce
(cherry picked from commit 016279b71e74700c18f2270649cb7567ae94505f)

commit_message:
Do not start nova-network in the notification func test

The notification sample tests uses neutron from day 0 but somehow it
also starts the nova-network service. This is unnecessary so this patch
removes it.

Change-Id: Ieac9791928822b26e590d99965632225acb9a464

commit_message:
CephFs-provisioner: fix cephfs storageclass

This is to remove invalid key "userSecretName" for
cephfs storageclass as we are having toruble to provision
a pvc with cephfs storageclass with "userSecretName" key .

Failed to provision volume with StorageClass
"cephfs": invalid option "userSecretName"

Change-Id: Ide52987c9f8ef8fc2327bf30747395e70dc05f99

commit_message:
Elasticsearch: Use openstackhelm elasticsearch-s3 image as default

This updates the Elasticsearch chart to use the elasticsearch-s3
image built from the openstack-helm-images Dockerfile instead of
using the previous image from a personal repository

Change-Id: I4d6b18aea11920de33ce1f4b63d39c18cd2b98d3

commit_message:
Fix helm-toolkit snippet for statefulset updates

This fixes the incorrect statefulset update helm-toolkit
snippet, as the previous implementation used incorrect keys
and fields for statefulset updates. See below:

https://kubernetes.io/docs/tutorials/stateful-application/basic-stateful-set/#updating-statefulsets
https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/68397

Change-Id: I5044460f19f0c824b08f99a90472c2e4a0e53e52

subject: Switch bindep fallback testing to openSUSE Leap 15.x
messages: [{'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2019-05-20 14:23:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2019-05-20 16:33:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2019-05-23 21:30:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2019-05-20 14:23:48.000000000', 'message': "Switch bindep fallback testing to openSUSE Leap 15.x

openSUSE Leap 42.3 is end of life in June 2019 so testing
it further doesn't make a whole lot of sense. instead we're
adding openSUSE Leap 15 (referring to openSUSE leap 15.0 at
the moment but once the infrastructure for Leap 15.1 has been
built it will be updated to the leap 15.x nodepool image). The
main reason why we can do this cleanup now is because there
has been a policy shift with openSUSE Leap 15: the minor releases
like 15.1 and 15.2 are similar to centos 7.x releases, they
should be all backward compatible so referring to it as leap15
is the correct thing to do.

Change-Id: I7ec755e678a3dfe45efad9104884df3daf315d2c
"}]
commit_message:
Switch bindep fallback testing to openSUSE Leap 15.x

openSUSE Leap 42.3 is end of life in June 2019 so testing
it further doesn't make a whole lot of sense. instead we're
adding openSUSE Leap 15 (referring to openSUSE leap 15.0 at
the moment but once the infrastructure for Leap 15.1 has been
built it will be updated to the leap 15.x nodepool image). The
main reason why we can do this cleanup now is because there
has been a policy shift with openSUSE Leap 15: the minor releases
like 15.1 and 15.2 are similar to centos 7.x releases, they
should be all backward compatible so referring to it as leap15
is the correct thing to do.

Change-Id: I7ec755e678a3dfe45efad9104884df3daf315d2c

commit_message:
Create 'Backport-Candidate' for Octavia repos

The Octavia team would like to enabled passive voting on patches
for backport candidates. This means that backport candidate votes
will not block a patch from merging, but will allow the team to
better track patches that should be backported.

Change-Id: Ib75714649848538e9fed171abd0b11f6fbc55503

commit_message:
Fix exception message

Fixes wording of the exception message, and also notes that the
templates directory may be inaccessible due to permission denied. This
could be caused by using a remote mounted (nfs/sshfs) directory that is
not accessible by root.

Change-Id: I7210831eafea825a3e7f4209c79b07a0b2510dac

commit_message:
List ha router count should not include dvr local router

Due to the class inheriting order the dvr local router will
be counted to the l3 agent restart query. This will cause
l3 agent run the ha port down action. This patch renames
the function to avoid that.

Closes-Bug: #1825787
Change-Id: Id965a6140ae9a06e0b6707800933cbc14bf5bf3f
(cherry picked from commit 8f2fc1ee5ee0d5cf8f412fa510adb87f3ed5f4b2)

commit_message:
Use InstanceList.get_count_by_hosts when deleting a compute service

This resolves the TODO in the delete service API code by using the
InstanceList.get_count_by_hosts method which is a simpler COUNT
query function rather than get_uuids_by_host.

Change-Id: I7de2526b72c2c080f314419792e4c6766907872d

commit_message:
refactor nova-manage archive_deleted_rows

In Change I408c22d8eada0518ec5d685213f250e8e3dae76e we want to be able
to archive records before a certain date. Without this patch,it will
require a few modifications to records in instance_actions,
instance_actions_events and migrations tables as they are handled
separately from other tables.

However, refactoring the archiving workflow to archive all dependent
tables in same function '_archive_if_instance_deleted()' allows archiving
without updating rows in those table. This is much cleaner.

Change-Id: I9725f752f8aef8066f7c9705e87610cad887bf8e

commit_message:
Only call _fill_provider_mapping if claim succeeds

During re-schedule condutor takes the next Selecton object from the
host list and tries to allocate the requested resources on the host in
the Selection object. So far the conductor also tried to find the
resource provide mapping for such allocation even if the resource claim
is failed. This is unnecessary. This patch makes sure that mapping is
tried to be calculated if the claim succeeds first.

Change-Id: I9944398c38d11466d27c2a4b24035b26d264b000
Closes-Bug: #1822262
(cherry picked from commit a9324ad84c6ef9b645643e8087f0f200d0ab1e88)

commit_message:
Skip _exclude_nested_providers() if not nested

In rocky cycle, 'GET /allocation_candidates' started to be aware of
nested providers from microversion 1.29, namely, it can have multiple
allocations from multiple resource providers in the same tree in the
allocation requests.

To keep the behavior of microversion before 1.29, it added a filters
to exculde nested providers being unaware of the nested architecture.
However that function "_exclude_nested_providers()" is very heavy
and is executed even if there is no nested provider in the environment
when microversion < 1.29.

This patch changes it to skip it if there is no nested provider.

Since _exclude_nested_providers() should be done before limitting
the candidates, this patch also moves it from hander file to the
deeper layer.

This is manually backported from the placement repository:
commit 727fb88dccfe8461cc40ae53ca2d4e40fd2a9c3c

Change-Id: I4efdc65395e69a6d33fba927018d003cce26fa68
Closes-Bug: #1828937

[{'created': '2019-05-21 09:53:54.000000000', 'message': "Stop logging traceback when skipping quiesce

During snapshot of a volume-backed instance, we attempt to quiesce the
instance before doing the snapshot. If quiesce is not supported or the
qemu guest agent is not enabled, we will skip the quiesce and move on
to the snapshot.

Because quiesce is a call to nova-compute over RPC, when the libvirt
driver raises QemuGuestAgentNotEnabled, oslo.messaging will append the
full traceback to the exception message [1] for the remote caller. So,
a LOG.info(..., exp) log of the exception object will result in a log
of the full traceback. Logging of the full traceback causes confusion
for those debugging CI failures.

We would rather not log the full traceback in this case where we are
catching the exception and emitting an INFO message, so we should use
exp.format_message() instead of oslo.messaging's __str__ override.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/40c25c2/oslo_messaging/_drivers/common.py#L212

Related-Bug: #1824315

Change-Id: Ibfedcb8814437c53081f5a2993ab84b25d73e557
(cherry picked from commit 66070416ab670daf4734f2c30ad2df5d96e615e6)
"}]
commit_message:
Stop logging traceback when skipping quiesce

During snapshot of a volume-backed instance, we attempt to quiesce the
instance before doing the snapshot. If quiesce is not supported or the
qemu guest agent is not enabled, we will skip the quiesce and move on
to the snapshot.

Because quiesce is a call to nova-compute over RPC, when the libvirt
driver raises QemuGuestAgentNotEnabled, oslo.messaging will append the
full traceback to the exception message [1] for the remote caller. So,
a LOG.info(..., exp) log of the exception object will result in a log
of the full traceback. Logging of the full traceback causes confusion
for those debugging CI failures.

We would rather not log the full traceback in this case where we are
catching the exception and emitting an INFO message, so we should use
exp.format_message() instead of oslo.messaging's __str__ override.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/40c25c2/oslo_messaging/_drivers/common.py#L212

Related-Bug: #1824315

Change-Id: Ibfedcb8814437c53081f5a2993ab84b25d73e557
(cherry picked from commit 66070416ab670daf4734f2c30ad2df5d96e615e6)

commit_message:
Handle placement error during re-schedule

If claim_resources or _fill_provider_mapping calls fail due to placement
error then the re-scheduling stops and the instance is not put into
ERROR state.

This patch adds proper exception handling to these cases.

Change-Id: I78fc2312274471a7bd85a263de12cc5a0b19fd10
Closes-Bug: #1819460
(cherry picked from commit b096d9303acfea81ca56394cab681d2b2eed2d91)

'}, {'account_id': 15554, 'date': '2018-09-20 12:30:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

First of all thank you for this change and sorry for my slow reaction.

This may be a good step to simplify testing neutron changes with recent (merged, but not yet released) neutron-lib dependencies.

I'm not sure though if this is what I was looking for. Usually I do run pep8 and unit tests before uploading any change. When my neutron changes depend on open neutron-lib changes I usually cross-test them by having a local hack like this in my neutron repo:

 -neutron-lib>=1.18.0 # Apache-2.0
 +-e git+ssh://127.0.0.1/home/ebenrom/src/os/openstack/neutron-lib@61e2a98ed0994e2887c901613a4d8fc4f205a093#egg=neutron-lib

This is relatively easy for me because there's no need for sophisticated environment setup and the unit test suite runs under 10 minutes.

Not seeing the results of the more complex jobs (requiring complex test environments and/or running long) is bothering me more. For example for this change series I haven't seen a proper functional/fullstack/tempest run since we started working on it: https://review.openstack.org/574783.

I will definitely re-check them when we cut the next neutron-lib release (that will contain the dependent changes) and I hope I will have no surprises then.

I was thinking (or maybe daydreaming :-) about something like this: When a patch Depends-On an open neutron-lib change we could install that in the test job. But when there's no Depends-On or when the Depends-On was merged already we could fall back to testing with the latest neutron-lib release (but do all this only in the check queue, and leave the gate queue untouched). So far no matter how much zuul documentation I read I don't see if this is doable. Maybe it's not. Or maybe it's just not feasible."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2018-09-20 13:43:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

In case of tox, zuul v3 installs all python packages from PyPI (based on upper-constraints.txt) unless they are specified in required-projects in .zuul.yaml (or other job definitions like openstack-zuul-jobs). This is the main background that we need this kind of change.'}, {'account_id': 27654, 'date': '2018-09-20 19:28:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 27654, 'date': '2018-09-20 19:39:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 5367, 'date': '2018-09-21 17:20:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)

Bence: I can certainly understand what you are wanting to do/test, but I just spoke with the infra team and they don't support conditional logic based on the depends-on patch nor recommend it.


If we are wanting to test things at a functional level with neutron-lib, it seems our best option is just to test when neutron-lib is released with the desired changes. In most cases its fairly low risk because the code that goes into neutron-lib is effectively dormant until consumed. There are some cases this is not true, but for the most part it is.


That said, does the neutron-lib non-voting job even buy us anything as proposed by this patch??

We appear to already be running a periodic of neutron with neutron-lib/master py35 [1]. I'm starting to think [1] is enough and we shouldn't even add this non-voting job (herein).


What do people think?


[1] http://logs.openstack.org/periodic/git.openstack.org/openstack/neutron/master/openstack-tox-py35-with-neutron-lib-master/"}, {'account_id': 27654, 'date': '2018-09-21 20:09:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> (3 comments)
 > 
 > Bence: I can certainly understand what you are wanting to do/test,
 > but I just spoke with the infra team and they don't support
 > conditional logic based on the depends-on patch nor recommend it.
 > 
 > 
 > If we are wanting to test things at a functional level with
 > neutron-lib, it seems our best option is just to test when
 > neutron-lib is released with the desired changes. In most cases its
 > fairly low risk because the code that goes into neutron-lib is
 > effectively dormant until consumed. There are some cases this is
 > not true, but for the most part it is.
 > 
 > 
 > That said, does the neutron-lib non-voting job even buy us anything
 > as proposed by this patch??
 > 
 > We appear to already be running a periodic of neutron with
 > neutron-lib/master py35 [1]. I'm starting to think [1] is enough
 > and we shouldn't even add this non-voting job (herein).
 > 
 > 
 > What do people think?
 > 
 > 
 > [1] http://logs.openstack.org/periodic/git.openstack.org/openstack/neutron/master/openstack-tox-py35-with-neutron-lib-master/

There were several times that I wanted to test neutron's patch with neutron-lib master, for example when I was implementing the filter validation feature: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/topic:bug/1749820+(status:open+OR+status:merged) . Having unit/functional/tempest jobs against neutron-lib's master is useful when the implementation is consistent of changes in both neutron and neutron-lib sides. In this case, the neutron-lib-master job allows me to test the neutron's code without waiting for the merging and release of the neutron-lib's patch and the bumping of upper-constraints which could take a few days or weeks.

I think what this patch offers is a convenient way to test neutron's code with pre-release of neutron-lib, which is a common needs. You can see there are a few patches [1][2][3] that we are not able to verify in the CI due to the missing of neutron-lib release.

Without such neutron-lib-master jobs, what we did is to request and wait for a newer release of neutron-lib, which could take a while. However, what might happen is that the newer release of neutron-lib still have some problems and I needed to patch the neutron-lib again and requested another release. This back-and-forth is not efficient and having a pre-release tests can help with it.

The periodic job couldn't solve the problem because it couldn't enable us to test patches that are unmerged. However, testing un-merged neutron's patch with neutron-lib master is currently the pain point.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/568526/
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/424468/
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+project:openstack/neutron+branch:master+topic:minimum-bandwidth-allocation-placement-api"}, {'account_id': 5367, 'date': '2018-09-21 20:39:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I still don't see this patch solving the problems discussed per say.
The only job this current patch adds is the unit tests with py35 against neutron-lib master.


So for example in the patches referenced in Hongbin's comment above, this py35 with neutron-lib master job might pass, but all other jobs would still fail because they are still using neutron-lib from PyPI.
We could add some functional test jobs that use neutron-lib master too, but again only they would pass in this example.


In addition these jobs would run for each neutron patch. We don't really need them to run that often, only in certain cases it seems so that might lead to extra infra resources used.


I'm not against adding such jobs, I just want to make sure we are making the right decision and getting benefit from it.


Perhaps we should consider having neutron just use neutron-lib master??!
As I mentioned almost all changes in lib are dormant until consumed and for those that aren't we could use dependencies. We might break every now and then, but at least we know we're broken right away :)"}, {'account_id': 27654, 'date': '2018-09-21 21:56:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> I still don't see this patch solving the problems discussed per
 > say.
 > The only job this current patch adds is the unit tests with py35
 > against neutron-lib master.
 > 
 > 
 > So for example in the patches referenced in Hongbin's comment
 > above, this py35 with neutron-lib master job might pass, but all
 > other jobs would still fail because they are still using
 > neutron-lib from PyPI.

What I would check is the result of py35 with neutron-lib master job. If this job fails, it will show me error and trace so that I can fix problem earlier. If this job doesn't exist, I won't know the problem until a newer release of neutron-lib.

 > We could add some functional test jobs that use neutron-lib master
 > too, but again only they would pass in this example.
 > 
 > 
 > In addition these jobs would run for each neutron patch. We don't
 > really need them to run that often, only in certain cases it seems
 > so that might lead to extra infra resources used.

This is a good point. If we want to save the extra infra resources used by this job, we can turn the job as experimental job so that it won't be triggered unless we explicitly trigger it.

 > 
 > 
 > I'm not against adding such jobs, I just want to make sure we are
 > making the right decision and getting benefit from it.
 > 
 > 
 > Perhaps we should consider having neutron just use neutron-lib
 > master??!
 > As I mentioned almost all changes in lib are dormant until consumed
 > and for those that aren't we could use dependencies. We might break
 > every now and then, but at least we know we're broken right away :)"}, {'account_id': 15554, 'date': '2018-09-24 12:07:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

> Bence: I can certainly understand what you are wanting to do/test,
 > but I just spoke with the infra team and they don't support
 > conditional logic based on the depends-on patch nor recommend it.

I'm a bit sad to hear that. But thank you for asking the infra team. It's good to know.

 > If we are wanting to test things at a functional level with
 > neutron-lib, it seems our best option is just to test when
 > neutron-lib is released with the desired changes. In most cases its
 > fairly low risk because the code that goes into neutron-lib is
 > effectively dormant until consumed. There are some cases this is
 > not true, but for the most part it is.

I agree. This lack of test coverage is not risky for neutron or neutron-lib releases. At worst the developer of the feature with not-yet-released neutron-lib dependencies gets a surprise later than ideal.

 > That said, does the neutron-lib non-voting job even buy us anything
 > as proposed by this patch??

Personally to me it does not. I already have the habit of running the unit test suite against the not-yet-released dependencies because that's easy and fast.

If infra folks do not recommend conditional logic in test jobs then I don't see a way to solve this problem purely from the CI environment. On the other hand I may have another idea. Consider the usual 'do not merge' hack for tox-based test jobs. We could do something similar for devstack-based test jobs. For example if I have a neutron patch series all red in the gate because of the missing neutron-lib dependencies then I could add an extra DNM patch on top which could install the neutron-lib version I want. I think there's probably a devstack-get hook that gets called after devstack installs everything but before the tests are run.

This would obviously not fix the test results of the changes below, but we could have real test results on the DNM patch. This is extra work of course for each patch series and for each change in the dependencies, but in return it gets gate test results for the developer. But not more work than the dummy patch approach. Could be documented similarly too. What do you think?

I'd like to try putting this together when I have some free time for it."}, {'account_id': 5367, 'date': '2018-09-26 16:01:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm still pondering what it would look like if neutron used neutron-lib/master during dev and then we just pinned a lib version when we started cutting the RCs. This would mean we are using/testing with neutron-lib master all the time and also don't need to wait for lib releases.


I take it others think that's too risky?"}, {'account_id': 13995, 'date': '2018-09-26 18:46:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I personally don't think it is too risky - it just imposes more of a burden on the person committing neutron-lib code to make sure they are not breaking stadium projects that they may not be knowledgeable or care about.  But I think that is fundamentally a solvable CI problem.

I just want python 3.6 for all the things."}, {'account_id': 13995, 'date': '2018-09-26 19:28:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Could we use the openstack-tox-py35-with-neutron-lib-master [1] for this task?

[1] https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs/tree/zuul.d/jobs.yaml#n647'}, {'account_id': 15554, 'date': '2018-09-27 14:01:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> I'm still pondering what it would look like if neutron used
 > neutron-lib/master during dev and then we just pinned a lib version
 > when we started cutting the RCs. This would mean we are
 > using/testing with neutron-lib master all the time and also don't
 > need to wait for lib releases.

We could test against neutron-lib master in the check queue. But since that does not converge to testing what is actually released we may want to consider still testing with the latest neutron-lib release either in the gate queue or in the release queue.

Or change almost all check jobs to test against neutron-lib master but keep one unit test job still testing against the latest release.

If we want to experiment with one of these options we may want to do this early in the release cycle to see how it works at the milestone releases."}, {'account_id': 5367, 'date': '2018-09-27 19:53:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Bence: TBH I'm not fully understanding why we'd want to leave some jobs testing the latest neutron-lib release.


The way I was seeing it, we run all jobs with neutron-lib master during dev of a release. Once we reach RC time, we will release a formal version of neutron-lib (based on master of lib which we've already been testing with in neutron in this scenario). At that point we also need to cut the neutron branch and along with that we will cap/specify the version of neutron-lib in the requirements.txt and update the in repo jobs to not pull from source (we are now keep per-release zuul config in repo)... This is basically what other projects that use siblings do so I'm not sure how its different here."}, {'account_id': 4694, 'date': '2018-10-02 23:27:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Boden,

What you are saying is that other projects with libraries similar to neutron-lib do is test against their library master during the development cycle and at the end of the cycle they just specify the version of their lib? Can you point to an example of this?

I find the latest scenario you propose interesting'}, {'account_id': 5367, 'date': '2018-10-03 14:01:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Miguel I'll use vmware-nsx as an example because I'm so familiar with it.


In our master branch, we pull a number of networking dependencies from master src via 'required-projects' in our zuul config [1]. We also test with them from master src for local testing by using pip install to install them dynamically [2].


Once a stable branch is cut at the end of a release we remove them from required-projects in our zuul config [3] and they are specified in requirements.txt with their released version from PyPI [4]. At this point these dependencies are no longer pulled from git master src and are instead pulled from PyPI.


I thought about this approach a bit more and while I do (think) I like what it gives us in neutron, I believe it also implies that our "active/current" consumers would need to follow suit. Otherwise they won't be up to date with neutron; e.g. they work with neutron-lib x.y.z but neutron works with neutron-lib/master...

While certainly all such consumers could take this approach, what I described above (the switch from using neutron-lib master to released version at the end of a release) has be done for all such projects. So it requires a bit more work at the end of a release and something teams would need to remember to do.


With that in mind I'm on the fence here... Was hoping someone would come along and persuade me one way or the other :)


[1] https://github.com/openstack/vmware-nsx/blob/master/.zuul.yaml
[2] https://github.com/openstack/vmware-nsx/blob/master/tox.ini#L31
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/605847/7/.zuul.yaml
[4] https://github.com/openstack/vmware-nsx/blob/stable/rocky/requirements.txt'}, {'account_id': 5367, 'date': '2018-10-03 14:01:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 4694, 'date': '2018-10-03 20:13:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Thanks Boden for your follow up. I agree. If we decide to test Neutron with neutron-lib master, we would need the same change in all our consumers. Given that and the fact that it is relatively easy to release neutron-lib when we need to test functionality in Neutron master, my opinion is that we should continue the way we are currently'}, {'account_id': 5367, 'date': '2018-10-16 19:00:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 5367, 'date': '2018-10-16 19:00:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow-1

Just in testing mode'}, {'account_id': 26622, 'date': '2018-10-16 20:37:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Build succeeded.

- neutron http://cloudbase-ci.com/neutron/602748/3 : SUCCESS in 1h 36m 40s'}, {'account_id': 5367, 'date': '2019-05-23 20:17:51.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Not much interest in this one. Abandon until someone has interest/cycles.'}]

commit_message:
py35 tox target and zuul job for neutron-lib master

This patch adds support for testing with neutron-lib master. Such
support allows developers to run py35 unit tests with neutron-lib
master using a tox target, as well a non-voting job that will do the
same in the gate. The intention is to provide an initial means to
ensure a neutron change works with neutron-lib master as per our
discussion at the stein PTG.

Change-Id: I7bf2ee0d4ccc9c3857e437cb57ce921f70b89057

commit_message:
Add DIB_LOCAL_IMAGE to use ubuntu local cloud image

Adds the ability to set $DIB_LOCAL_IMAGE to use as the base
cloud image for a Ubuntu image build. Download image from
internet is not prerequisite with $DIB_LOCAL_IMAGE
to set the cached base cloud image location.

Change-Id: I94eb0c21348ad087b499c8dc91491288955fdb1b

commit_message:
Update Calico Felix to v3

Moving to v3 requires etcd3, which uses a new L4 gateway setup and
deprecates v2 proxy. The role configuration is updated to use the
etcd3 L4 gateway.

This also includes several dependent fixes and moves the Calico
test to use the integrated repo's Calico scenario.

Combined backport of:
https://review.opendev.org/#/c/641483/
https://review.opendev.org/#/c/645971/
https://review.opendev.org/#/c/659710/
https://review.opendev.org/#/c/659711/

Also pulls in the updated tests-repo-clone from
I67ebe9e813c95a3a8bcf204678ddccbcea7a45cd so that the depends-on
function in this patch works.

openSUSE 42.3 testing is removed since this version is EOL soon and
our ability to build LXC containers on 42.3 is broken/unmaintained.

Depends-On: I9fb16b7f046530efc124e760bc7870c13b4e8d32
Depends-On: I746b9dbb090dd484a36e826f06beda1eba3f55f4
Depends-On: Iaf392898c072ac4b39d878bb27654406c5ab0d8b

(cherry picked from commit a4181a77c10c62dd7205b5452fbb4a63391c1e13)

commit_message:
Fix 403 issue when creating load balancers

The Octavia dashboard code was attempting to access flavor profile
information when creating a load balancer. Flavor profiles are
administrator only objects that cannot be accessed by users with
the default RBAC.
This patch removes the code attempting to access the flavor profile
as it is not necessary.

Change-Id: Ic11d8b84f61c1fd8c97a81f2e47745a339396336
Story: 2005759
Task: 33467

commit_message:
Cap bandit below 1.6.0 version and update sphinx and limit monotonic.

Bandit 1.6.0 accidentally changed how to exclusion list option is
handled and breaks our use of it. Cap to the previous version until
bandit has has fixed the problem.

Sphinx 2.0 no longer works on python 2.7, so need to start capping it
there as well.

Limit monotonic to python < 3.3 and reflect the changes to
openstack/requirements introduced
in change Ib8c1bf08f5fa7463911602b0df19315907c81e04.

Co-Authored-By: Stephen Finucane <sfinucan@redhat.com>
Co-Authored-By: Hervé Beraud <hberaud@redhat.com>

Change-Id: I4c2a19fae55e8cfea2d5ae9603a1fb086b5db1bf

commit_message:
Add set require-osd-release command to upgrade.

To access all ceph features for a new release,
require-osd-release must be set to the current
release. Else, features will not be available
and ceph health gives a warning on luminous.
Here, we add logic to wait for all ceph instances
to reach the same version then run the command
to set require-osd-release.

Add check to run only on leader and on versions
luminous and above.

Add wait logic for ceph version convergence.

Add call to set require-osd-release to current
release.

Add subprocess error handling for roll_monitor_cluster
try block.

Fixes LP Bug #1828630
Change-Id: Ieb02f7bc5df96f7bb9a6ff926e71e86df1a4421f

commit_message:
Skip existing VMs when hosts apply force_config_drive

When hosts apply config `CONF.force_config_drive=True`, the existing
VMs shouldn't be enforced to must have config drive device. For they
may have been cloud-inited via metadata service, and may not need and
have any config drive device ever. In contrast, the newly being-built
ones should. Instance attr `launched_at` serves as an apparent flag
to distinguish the two kinds of VMs.

When hard reboots happend, existing VMs skip config drive enforcement,
and therefore avoid hitting 'No such file or directory (config drive
device)' error.

Change-Id: I0558ece92f8657c2f6294e07965c619eb7c8dfcf
Closes-Bug: #1827492

commit_message:
Make Event logging more useful by default

Log messages like:

ChassisGatewayAgentEvent : Matched Chassis, create, None None

are not particularly useful. This adds a default repr to RowEvents
and also a Row stringifier (which eventually could go in the ovs
lib). Subclasses of RowEvent that rely on custom match functions
should write their own __repr__ methods.

Change-Id: Ice22858df465b37b973718be718673aab46193ce

commit_message:
Armada: Fix fluentbit typos in config overrides

This fixes a typo in the fluentbit configuration overrides in the
armada-lma manifest. The key used for declaring which parser to
use for syslog style entries was set to 'Parsers:' instead of
'Parser'. This is required to alleviate issues with fluentbit

commit_message:
Fixups from removing null provider protections

In the review of change I84baff29505550f3f20069ad5817784d0d1aaea6
a two details that were missed were identified:

* a writer context that could be a reader now that the changes
  are done

* a database return being sufficiently "dict-ish" to use directly
  when creating a named tuple.

Change-Id: Id07eee0b427e0d12fc429fd02e17706fb4447418

commit_message:
Fix IPA client when doing brownfield deployment of internal TLS

* Always use the FQDN supplied in the metadata.
* Read the metadata from network if hostname could not be determined.

These changes fix issues with deploying internal TLS after initialy
deploying without it (also known as a "brownfield deployment").

Change-Id: I9d1b4174dd349c29dc92079202176a11d3f85fe3
Co-Authored-By: Ade Lee <alee@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Set subparser argument required

When subparser argument is not provided by user
argparse return an error message not really useful for user:

    'Namespace' object has no attribute 'func'

This is due to the fact that when we launch the pbr in cli mode
the subparser argument is not mandatory (required) and directly
we try to execute a undefined function.

Set the subparser required is more helpful for users due to the
fact that argparse display the helping message with the available
sub-commands that users can use

These changes provides the following output if the argument is not
passed:

usage: pbr [-h] [-v] {sha,info,freeze} ...
main.py: error: too few arguments

Change-Id: I7982f9d40cb0979ddb89d7bc53964167f8e4b269

commit_message:
Fix white space handling in file names

Previously, when using data_files with a glob that matched a file with
whitespace in the name, pip would error with a message that the file
does not exist, e.g:

    error: can't copy 'ansible/roles/yatesr.timezone/templates/timezone-Arch': doesn't exist or not a regular file

The problem was that ansible/roles/yatesr.timezone/templates/timezone-Arch
was a truncated form of the actual filename:

    ansible/roles/yatesr.timezone/templates/timezone-Arch Linux.j2

Note the space in the filename and that it has been split on this space.

This change allows you to use a glob that matches files with whitespace
in the name. It does this by quoting the path.

Change-Id: Id2cc32e4e40c1f834b19756e922118d8526358d3
Fixes-Bug: 1810934

commit_message:
Packets getting lost during SNAT with too many connections

We have a problem with SNAT with too many connections using the
same source and destination on the network nodes.

In addition we can see in the conntrack table that the who
"instert_failed" increases.

This might be a generic problem with conntrack and linux.
We suspect that we encounter the following "limitation / bug"
in the kernel.

There seems to be a workaround to alleviate this behavior by
setting the -random-fully flag in iptables for port consumption.

This patch fixes the problem by adding the --random-fully to
the SNAT rules.

Conflicts:
    neutron/agent/linux/iptables_manager.py
    neutron/common/constants.py
    neutron/tests/unit/agent/l3/test_agent.py

Change-Id: I246c1f56df889bad9c7e140b56c3614124d80a19
Closes-Bug: #1814002

[{'created': '2018-10-15 16:39:26.000000000', 'message': "Change python3.5 job to python3.7 job on Stein+

This is a mechanically generated patch to add a unit test job running
under Python 3.7 and drop the Python 3.5 unit test job.

python3.5 was the only supported python3 version on Xenial. Now that
we have Bionic nodes supporting python3.6 and python3.7, let's switch
to testing with python3.7 in addition to python3.6 in Stein and
beyond.

See ML discussion here [1] for context.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2018-October/135626.html

Change-Id: Icc6cb4979b2523a0edfc6375c5c032bb8be76b9f

commit_message:
Add openstack-tox-py37 job

Enables py37 testing while also being more friendly with developer
environments where not all python versions may be available.

Runs the docs jobs last as that one is the least likely to be needed.

Tox min version is needed for the new options used inside.

Change-Id: Icc6cb4979b2523a0edfc6375c5c032bb8be76b9f
Story: #2004073
Task: #27440

commit_message:
Fix KeyError when image was deleted

KeyError was raised when volume was created from image and
then this image is deleted. THis patch adds additional check
to avoid such situations.

Closes-Bug: #1826690
Change-Id: I85712fd9587d8815d2f3c74227ded9a4f62296f3
(cherry picked from commit a1559be7786f8f944cb01b4f502c9c54ae2c7baf)

Update container docs with podman commands replacing docker

This patch updates tripleo docs with podman command equivalents
replacing the old docker ones.

All replaced commands have been tested on a CentOS 7 standalone
environment and are proven to work.

commit_message:
Correct OVN driver feature matrix

We discovered that the OVN driver only supports the SOURCE_IP load
balancing algorithm instead of the previously listed ROUND_ROBIN.

Change-Id: I1bf46b3846088ceede848e8288ed68d2ba4df061

commit_message:
Add missing link between healthcheck unit and main service

Until now, if we stop the main service, we might encounter an issue
where the healthcheck is running, and we end up with two error:
- systemctl stop <container> returns "1"
- container is in Exited(137) state

[root@undercloud ~]# systemctl stop tripleo_nova_compute
Job for tripleo_nova_compute.service canceled.
[root@undercloud ~]# echo $?
1
podman ps -a | grep nova_compute
(...) 27 minutes ago  Exited (137) 3 minutes ago nova_compute

Using the "PartOf" within the healthecheck ensures it's stopped when the
main service is stopped.
Adding the "Requires" on the main service unit allows to ensure the
healthcheck is started as a dependency.

Change-Id: I681fa0eb225d43ecbaa1b765f6761dd07031bce1
Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/660681
(cherry picked from commit 7e85445bef044153b79c08166738d76361999db0)

@Ade Lee, Thanks for the specs, overall the design and API calls looks to good to me from kubernetes perspective'}, {'account_id': 19457, 'date': '2018-09-19 06:59:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi, Ade Lee Any update on this, I have created a WIP PR in kubernetes
https://github.com/kubernetes/cloud-provider-openstack/pull/286,
I have tested with storing secret id in k8s etcd, but we cannot use this approach for long, as secrets are getting collected in barbican because of no notification of secret deletion from k8s, so we have to implement this specs and store only KEK in barbican'}, {'account_id': 9914, 'date': '2018-09-20 17:00:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

The consensus at the PTG was that this was a lower priority feature because 

1) you have the workaround we discussed, albeit with the problem of secrets piling up as you described. (So maybe that won't work).

2) there is another perhaps even better alternative:  citadel
  https://github.com/enj/citadel

Have you looked into citadel?  Is there a reason why this will not meet your needs?  If so, the reasons why will be useful for us to justify prioritizing this work.  Also, other user cases/drivers will help too.

We just don't want to end up creating a feature that no one will end up using."}, {'account_id': 19457, 'date': '2018-09-21 06:52:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Set force_config_drive only when OVNMetadata is disabled

There are usecases when operator wants to talk to metadata API from
config-drive script (e.g. using curl to get data from metadata). That
means it makes sense to have OVN Metadata Agent deployed while forcing
config-drive to be used.

This patch sets force_config_drive to true only when OVNMetadataEnable
is set to false. If it's set to true then it doesn't touch
force_config_drive option, leaving it up to environment to define it.
(The default for force_config_drive is false.)

Closes-Bug: #1830179
Change-Id: Ib956ff2f521b9853c58eaa5500836c692dd9321d

commit_message:
Write TLS config under section [client] in tripleo.cnf

the SQL shell 'mysql' currently cannot parse config under section
[tripleo] as option bind-address is not supported in mariadb (only
supported in mysql and PyMySQL).

Generate a proper TLS config under section [client] so that the
mysql shell can connect to the mysql server with the proper TLS
settings.

Change-Id: Icaaee64b6f491bf80fde2a8a44c6b28727493e13
Closes-Bug: #1829758

Blueprint for making soft deletions optional

Barbican currently does soft deletions on some resources. This gives
the option for the admin to turn this off and enable hard deletions.

commit_message:
Replace orders quota with secrets reservation system

This blueprint specifies the current issues with order quota
enforcement and proposes the removal of the orders quota,
implementation of a secrets reservation system to handle secret
quota enforcement when creating orders, and implementation of
checks against the secrets quota at every step of order creation.

Orders can also take a significant amount of time to create (such as in
the case of certificates), which raises the question of whether there
will be any secrets available for the order when it is finished creating
(what if orders quota is greater than secrets
quota and the secrets quota is exceeded?).

This blueprint proposes removal of the orders quota, implementation of a
system to reserve secrets when an order is placed, and the
implementation of secret quota checks at every step of order creation
(when an order is placed, when a call to the plugin is made, and when a
secret is returned by the plugin).

Change-Id: Ic9381210208cc775c0622bf88eef1bf599aa1392

[{'created': '2015-01-20 14:56:40.000000000', 'message': "Support concurrent updates on the orders API resource

Currently if a PUT request is made to an existing orders resource, the
updated order metadata is sent as an argument to an enqueued RPC task
to worker nodes. If subsequent PUT requests are made to the same order,
multiple RPC tasks will be enqueued and potentially processed by

commit_message:
Support concurrent updates on the orders API resource

Currently if a PUT request is made to an existing orders resource, the
updated order metadata is sent as an argument to an enqueued RPC task
to worker nodes. If subsequent PUT requests are made to the same order,
multiple RPC tasks will be enqueued and potentially processed by
multiple worker nodes. Hence the sequence of processing these RPC tasks
is not guaranteed to be the same as the PUT requests were received.
This blueprint seeks to avoid this race condition. A motivation for
this feature is to support reliably updating SSL certificate orders 'in
flight', say to correct a contact email address. Another benefit is
limiting the amount of updates that can be made to a given order,
reducing the possibility of a denial of service attack via the orders
resource.

Change-Id: Ic5db6ed73310b951d73e7f2fe0cbc17711966038
Implements: blueprint api-orders-support-concurrent-updates
APIImpact: Adds 400 response if too many PUT requests to same order
SecurityImpact: Should help mitigate DoS attack on order via PUTs
DocImpact: Update orders resource doc to mention 400 response

[{'created': '2015-04-30 04:40:01.000000000', 'message': "Add Crypto/HSM MKEK Rotation Support

Currently Barbican has no means to migrate secrets encrypted with a
crypto/HSM-style plugin to a new master key encryption key (MKEK) and
its associated wrapped project KEKs. This blueprint proposes adding a
new Barbican service process that supports completing the rotation of
secrets to a new master key encryption key (MKEK) and a new wrapped
project KEK. This process would be started after deployers, out of
band: (1) generate new MKEK and HMAC signing keys with a binding to new
labels, and then (2) replicate these keys to other HSMs that may be in
the high availability (HA) group, and then (3) update Barbican's config
file to reference these new labels, and finally (4) restart the
Barbican nodes. The proposed process would then migrate secrets from
encryption via the old keys to encryption via the new ones.

Change-Id: Iccdfca4f309c50b7507f0a0992bec561045784f0
Implements: blueprint add-crypto-mkek-rotation-support
SecurityImpact: Rotates and migrates secrets to new KEKs.
DocImpact: Add information on running KEK migration process.

commit_message:
Add Crypto/HSM MKEK Rotation Support

Currently Barbican has no means to migrate secrets encrypted with a
crypto/HSM-style plugin to a new master key encryption key (MKEK) and
its associated wrapped project KEKs. This blueprint proposes adding a
new Barbican service process that supports completing the rotation of
secrets to a new master key encryption key (MKEK) and a new wrapped
project KEK.

Note that unlike the similarly-named blueprint at
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/barbican/+spec/add-crypto-mkek-rotation-support-lightweight
this blueprint does call for re-encrypting secrets *and* wrapped
project KEKs, so the other blueprint is a 'lightweight' alternative to
this one.

This process would be started after deployers, out of
band: (1) generate new MKEK and HMAC signing keys with a binding to new
labels, and then (2) replicate these keys to other HSMs that may be in
the high availability (HA) group, and then (3) update Barbican's config
file to reference these new labels, and finally (4) restart the
Barbican nodes. The proposed process would then migrate secrets from
encryption via the old keys to encryption via the new ones.

Change-Id: Iccdfca4f309c50b7507f0a0992bec561045784f0
Implements: blueprint add-crypto-mkek-rotation-support
SecurityImpact: Rotates and migrates secrets to new KEKs.
DocImpact: Add information on running KEK migration process.

commit_message:
Set the lower limit of api_version for volume_type

In boot server API, the volume_type is supported by microversion 2.67.
Therefore, the lower limit of the volume_type should be added to the CLI
command, otherwise an exception will occur.

Co-Authored-By: Eric Xie <eric_xiett@163.com>

Closes-Bug: #1829854
Change-Id: Ie909c16568b017ca0acc802194140da7bece76c5

commit_message:
Display quotas per Cinder volume type

This patch makes Cinder volume type quotas visible in panels
related to volume creation (from volumes and images tabs).

Currently user is able to select a desired type, but if quotas are
set, there is no way to check if creating a volume is going to
succeed. With this patch two additional quota charts are displayed
so that end user can see if there is still available quota for
selected type.

This is a continued work of Mateusz Kowalski (#511472),
adapted to work with Rocky.

Closes-Bug: #1717342
Implements: blueprint quotas-per-cinder-volume-type

Change-Id: I6097f523b2ed6d9449a4b00f1c4510663da4dc7f

commit_message:
Rocky: Add missing monasca groups to inventory

Kolla is backporting all fixes for monasca to the stable/rocky branch.

This patch adds relevant groups to the inventory necessary to deploy
monasca. It should be compatible with versions kolla-ansible prior to
the monasca backport since the group changes are only additive.

We also disable grafana by default, instead use the monasca-grafana
service that is enabled automatically when monasca is enabled.

Change-Id: I35e2eb5bd96186537cfd085ecd611873bcd26801

commit_message:
[DHCP] Don't resync network if same port is alredy in cache

Sometimes when port is created on dhcp agent's side, it may happend
that same port is already in network cache.
Before this patch if port with same IP address was already in cache,
resync was rescheduled because of duplicate IPs found in cache.

Now resync will be scheduled only if duplicate IP address belongs to
port with different MAC address or different id.

Change-Id: I23afbc10725f5dc78e3c63e6e505ef89ba8dc4a5
Closes-Bug: #1824802

commit_message:
Point to OSH-images images

We now have a process for OSH-images image building,
using Zuul, so we should point the images by default to those
images, instead of pointing to stale images.

Without this, the osh-images build process is completely not
in use (and completely opaque to deployers), and updating the
osh-images process or patching its code has no impact on OSH.

This should fix it.

Change-Id: Ic00bd98c151669dc2485cd88e0e8c2ab05445959

[{'created': '2018-12-21 16:50:21.000000000', 'message': "Make 'destination' optional for live migration

You don't need to supply a destination host when live migrating and if
you don't nova will pick one for you. Enable this use case through some
command line foo.

Note that this is currently broken due to a bug in argparse [1]. We're
going to need to vendor yet more of argparse in cliff and resolve that
before this will work. The alternative I explored was making '--live' a
simple boolean flag and adding a second positional argument, but that
means either (a) we break things for users currently running something
like 'server migrate --live dest source' (dest and source would not be
swapped) or (b) we end up with an unintuitive command where the
destination positional argument comes before source positional and we'd
still break commands like 'server migrate --live dest --foo source'.

[1] https://bugs.python.org/issue9338

commit_message:
Make 'destination' optional for live migration

You don't need to supply a destination host when live migrating and if
you don't nova will pick one for you. Enable this use case through some
rather ugly hackery. Note that this solution was chosen after other
attempts were brought down by bugs in argparse [1].

[1] https://bugs.python.org/issue9338

Change-Id: I5d06ebac81c409cef244352f46ebde9c0b74aea9
Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <sfinucan@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1411190

commit_message:
Remove null root provider protections

A when root providers were added, a series of TODOs were
left in allocation candidate and resource provider data
handling. These TODOs should be removed once we are assured
that there are no null roots. That is the case now, given
that we had an online migration and a status check and now
(prior to this patch) there is a blocker migration and the
status check is an error instead of warning.

The release note for the change of the status check should
suffice for covering this. That is: it makes what it says,
True.

Story: 2005613
Task: 30860
Change-Id: I84baff29505550f3f20069ad5817784d0d1aaea6

commit_message:
Remove rootwrap configuration from neutron-keepalived-state-change

New IP command introduced by Ie3fe825d65408fc969c478767b411fe0156e9fbc
requires only privsep initialization. This patch removes the prisep
error FailedToDropPrivileges when executed under neutron-rootwrap.

Closes-Bug: #1823038

Change-Id: I6cde3c9dae7ffdccce49e88c3c79d1c379f291cf

commit_message:
Remove rootwrap configuration from neutron-keepalived-state-change

New IP command introduced by Ie3fe825d65408fc969c478767b411fe0156e9fbc
requires only privsep initialization. This patch removes the prisep
error FailedToDropPrivileges when executed under neutron-rootwrap.

Closes-Bug: #1823038

Change-Id: I6cde3c9dae7ffdccce49e88c3c79d1c379f291cf
(cherry picked from commit aacd11ab9f8f24291f369d23662b0cb6b3fe43e3)

commit_message:
Use a hash for lock names

Some tooz drivers do not support long lock names. For example, mysql locks must
be 64 characters at most. This hashes the lock name in order to fix the lock
name length.

Change-Id: I5f058ea1197f5c2ba062a9bc0b67c509c8252852

commit_message:
[DNM] Populate key_pairs from top_cell to child cells

This patch adds a keypair migration tool to repopulate missing
keypairs in the child cells by reading the correspoding records
from cell00 (the top cell in cells_v1).

This patch might be required for operators to migrate from cells_v1 to
cells_v2 if they face a situation where keypairs are missing in
the instance_extra tables of their child cells in case they were
running cells_v1 when the newton ``instance_obj.migrate_instance_keypairs``
migration was run.

Note that the top_api_context_manager targets the cells_v1 mother DB
while main_context_manager targets the child cells.

FYI: Its an ugly fix and hence the DNM.

Change-Id: I2d73976916e05a0ef722384244dbc9af7a16b466
Closes-Bug: #1761197

commit_message:
Change provider network segmentation ID in OVS agent

Added the ability to change the segmentation ID of a network
with ports bound to OVS agent. The rules, both in the integration
bridge and the physical bridge, to convert the internal VLAN tag
and the external segmentation ID (external VLAN tag) are deleted
and created again with the new value. The traffic from the tenant
networks will be tagged then with the new segmentation ID.

Added get network details agent RPC call to retrieve the information
of the updated network.

Partial-Bug: #1806052

Change-Id: I69f6f3ef717c3ed40218099b1f389afd3d39bd62

commit_message:
Get rid of lookup utils

With the new joining mechanism lookup utils for task executions
become useless and can be removed from the codebase.
Now all requests to the database will be perforemed directly from
a workflow controller.

Action defention cache was moved to mistral/engine/actions.py,
because it's needed only there.

Change-Id: If0d4403f5c61883ecfec4cfa14b98cc39aae5618

commit_message:
Allow to add env files to overcloud deploy script

In order to be able to manage new services added in new releases, like
CinderBackendPure when upgrading from 13 to 14, we need the ability
to enable services by adding the corresponding env file prior
to performing upgrade.

commit_message:
standalone/undercloud - post: use EndpointMap to fetch Keystone URL

Using EndpointMap to ensure we get the hostname/fqdn if possible
otherwise it fallbacks to the IP for Keystone public endpoint.

This is useful when the operator uses a certificate based on
hostname/fqdn and not an IP address.

Closes-Bug #1763776
Change-Id: Ifa9d55cca90caf5be0c83507cb47447e25311fce

Looks like a good start, but there's some prep work before we can go ahead with this as documented in [3,4]:

This patch needs to follow something along the lines of [1] and prepare/reference a patch like [2] in the networking-sfc repo. Then the patch you just proposed here should be also made dependent on patches that validate 'stadium compliance', in the sfc case that means:

1) patch that converts CLIs into OSC.
2) patch that makes tempest job gated and voting
3) patch that introduces grafana/periodic job
4) patch that provides releasenotes

Hope that makes sense.

Service Function Chaining API Reference

This commit copies the Service Function Chaining API documentation from
the networking-sfc repository to the neutron-lib repository and
disambiguates the parameter names.

Change-Id: I938b50ff6ff6aa50cfa87ae90e9295fd58f60dae

The json from ceph must go through .decode("UTF-8"), otherwise we get a
JSON object must be str, not 'bytes' error.

Change-Id: I5cdb4e766655a866699a18f1e367971fd1d310af
Closes-Bug: #1771552
'}, {'created': '2018-05-16 11:57:02.000000000', 'message': 'Fix rbd driver json loading

It looks like rbd.py sometimes gets some bytes, not strings, probably
this happens with the latest version of Ceph, and that's an issue only
with Python 3. I'm not sure why, but what I know, is that it's completely
breaking Debian with Python 3 and ceph Luminous release.

So, this patch first tests the json buffer comming from Ceph, and if it
isn't a string, it calls .decode("UTF-8").

Change-Id: I5cdb4e766655a866699a18f1e367971fd1d310af
Closes-Bug: #1771552

commit_message:
Fix rbd driver json loading

It looks like rbd.py sometimes gets some bytes, not strings, probably
this happens with the latest version of Ceph, and that's an issue only
with Python 3. I'm not sure why, but what I know, is that it's completely
breaking Debian with Python 3 and ceph Luminous release.

Convert byte buffers coming from Ceph to strings.

Co-Authored-By: Eric Harney <eharney@redhat.com>

subject: Docs: Improve vpnaas scenario
revisions:
[{'created': '2019-05-23 11:24:56.000000000', 'message': 'Docs: Improve vpnaas scenario

Sometimes Linux service ipsec not running will cause
ipsec pluto not working, as a result Neutron VPN service
not works as expect.

Add a note for check ipsec service before using VPN service.

Change-Id: I8219c5fb86ae79850e2c4bfe1b95d61dfad6552e
'}]
commit_message:
Docs: Improve vpnaas scenario

Sometimes Linux service ipsec not running will cause
ipsec pluto not working, as a result Neutron VPN service
not works as expect.

Add a note for check ipsec service before using VPN service.

Really good stuff! Kuba and I have been discussing it on IRC as I was concerned about races between the read lock and the resync operation.
He pointed out that multiple resync operations would occur.
I don't think this should be an issue as two resync's in should result in the second one being *almost* a 'noop', just taking time on listing bridges and interfaces ensuring all's correct.
On the other hand, this should only happen if the OVN bridge changes which is very unlikely (migration from ML2/OVS use case) so I'm ok with the current approach."}, {'account_id': 11975, 'date': '2019-04-25 15:54:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2019-05-03 21:26:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

commit_message:
metadata: Resync agent when misconfiguration is detected

In case of migration, the metadata agent is kept running with old
br-migration bridge cached in agent's attribute.  Everything else is
configured correctly but agent still uses old value.  This patch adds a
resync mechanism that's triggered by PortBindingChassisEvent in case
agent fails to use currently cached bridge and the bridge doesn't exist
on the system.

Closes-bug: #1824984
Change-Id: Ia17ad3476e61a729136622b4356ce59234ab023a

commit_message:
Use openstack-tox-docs for api-* jobs

Rebase build-api-* jobs on openstack-tox-docs so that teams
can control environment, similar to what we did for openstack-tox-docs.

The repos using the build-api jobs have already a tox.ini environment
set up, so no changes needed for these repos.

This is one step in phasing out build-sphinx jobs.

Change-Id: I2dc873739755cf68ff68bcbb4504db2c76507f53

commit_message:
Pass correct arguments to six.reraise

six.reraise input arguments are:
  six.reraise(exc_type, exc_value, exc_traceback=None)

This information is provided by sys.exc_info() and stored
in self.communication_error.

Trivial-Fix

Change-Id: Ibe68d8e36ca424da61a0a9eea20e622440c79464

commit_message:
Make sure to set umask 022 for nova_migration_target logins

On RHEL8 copy files for cold/live migration useing SSH in
nova_migration_target container use the wrong umask. With this
change we make sure to use 022 as umask in the nova_migration_target
container.

Closes-bug: #1829996

Change-Id: I354f153394009591e38773d0afc933ce38a8fdff
(cherry picked from commit 8ff689bc835836799fe4b51522aa2beb9d125cad)

commit_message:
Change "Missing Root Provider IDs" upgrade check to a failure

We want to drop the REST API compability code for resource
providers with no root_provider_id in Train, so to start
we should make the related upgrade check a failure rather
than a warning.

Change-Id: Ifd3c84ea3348fc9e6653838d6fba4a5eb864f01e
Story: 2005613
Task: 30921

commit_message:
Ignore config-samples and policy sample file in git

Sphinx generates files and directories like:
doc/source/_static/config-samples/
doc/source/_static/neutron.policy.yaml.sample

when is building docs pages.
Those files should be ignored in git and this patch adds it
to the .gitignore file.

Change-Id: I42d358bf062f3bcb2809fd762773246186ca4482

commit_message:
Set arp_notify to match ndisc_notify

A previous change [1] enabled ndisc_notify, which is the IPv6 equivalent
for IPv4's arp_notify.  Enable the latter to keep them consistent with
each other.

Change-Id: I15e8348585a9c0ee824a4c123677992010980b9e
Related-Bug: #1827927
(cherry picked from commit f3df90f2c0afa352d4dcf14463a9364c9080afe6)

commit_message:
Download and define base image if configured

When we build the image we need a base image to be defined.
For CentOS it's done automatically in client, but if we need to
build something else we need to download it and define it
explicitly.
base_image_url - URL of base image
base_image_path - path to save it on host

Change-Id: I10bd9868fcfd3a4d5992fc7d7b6200e908e75e25

Update description of valid whitelist for non-admin user

added with Ia5504da9a00bad689766aeda20255e10b7629f63.

commit_message:
Fix devstack plugin python3 support

The octavia-dashboard devstack plugin.sh script was calling
"python". This causes the plugin to fail on python3 only hosts.
This patch corrects this by using the devstack $PYTHON variable.

Change-Id: I18bc3ce532e163acc1d49daa84cd7c7495dbc777
Story: 2005761
Task: 33469

commit_message:
Windows: avoid passing conf objects to subprocesses

On Windows, cotyledon uses multiprocessing instead of forking. Meanwhile,
config objects as well as service manager objects aren't pickleable.

For this reason, we'll avoid passing unpickleable objects to subprocesses,
making all the required initialization on the subprocess side.

This change will allow ceilometer-polling to run on Windows.

Change-Id: Id51db8f06f295bb7019915b53e560df52456cbda
Closes-Bug: #1625602

commit_message:
Fix format file message field

The message field for these format files wasn't renamed when
the input field was renamed. This problem was masked by Monasca
which renames the message field back to 'message' for the Fluentd
Monasca output plugin.

Change-Id: I2674958b1e64efddbca4765fefa55431261648e6
Closes-Bug: #1819168

commit_message:
Add ability to provide qos_policy_id for port

Neutron API supports qos_policy defenition during port creation and
port object already contains qos_policy_id[1]
So this patch extends port_update method with the ability to provide
qos_policy_id in the addition to existing parameters.

[1] https://opendev.org/openstack/openstacksdk/src/branch/master/openstack/network/v2/port.py#L109

Change-Id: Iad837fababa8d9d0c604637d326b1b1253f13c05

commit_message:
Add support for vendor hooks

Add possibility to pass a hook in the vendor config, clouds-public.* or 
upon building a connection. This should be a string parameter - function
name to be executed. This gives possibility to register new services of 
the cloud automatically or alter behavior of the present services.
It would have not been necessary, if public clouds followed 
upstream-first aproach.

While we are here fix warnings on not closed files in the test_json

Change-Id: Ifd6c0847102af4f46e361dcb1a665829c77553b9
